Great! Now I have properly implemented the fix. Let me summarize what I've done:

## Understanding the Issue

The problem was that when `@JsonIdentityReference(alwaysAsId=true)` is applied to a class definition itself, Jackson was not properly recognizing this annotation to serialize all usages of that class as IDs. The current implementation only checked for the annotation on the specific field or property accessor, but not on the class type itself.

## The Solution

I modified the `findObjectReferenceInfo` method in `JacksonAnnotationIntrospector.java` to:

1. First, check for the `@JsonIdentityReference` annotation on the annotated member itself (the existing behavior)
2. If the `alwaysAsId` property is not already set to `true`, then check if the raw type of the annotated member has the `@JsonIdentityReference` annotation on its class definition
3. If the class type has the annotation, apply its `alwaysAsId` setting to the `ObjectIdInfo`

This ensures that when a class is annotated with `@JsonIdentityReference(alwaysAsId=true)` at the class level, all properties/fields of that type will be serialized as IDs, not just when the annotation is applied directly to the field.

## Code Changes

The key change was in the `findObjectReferenceInfo` method:

```java
@Override
public ObjectIdInfo findObjectReferenceInfo(Annotated ann, ObjectIdInfo objectIdInfo) {
    JsonIdentityReference ref = _findAnnotation(ann, JsonIdentityReference.class);
    if (ref != null) {
        objectIdInfo = objectIdInfo.withAlwaysAsId(ref.alwaysAsId());
    }

    // Also check if the type of the annotated member has @JsonIdentityReference
    // This handles the case where the annotation is on the class definition itself
    if (objectIdInfo != null && !objectIdInfo.getAlwaysAsId()) {
        // Get the type of the annotated member (field type, method return type, etc.)
        Class<?> type = ann.getRawType();
        if (type != null) {
            JsonIdentityReference typeRef = type.getAnnotation(JsonIdentityReference.class);
            if (typeRef != null) {
                objectIdInfo = objectIdInfo.withAlwaysAsId(typeRef.alwaysAsId());
            }
        }
    }
    return objectIdInfo;
}
```

This change ensures that when `@JsonIdentityReference(alwaysAsId=true)` is applied to a class definition, it will be properly recognized and applied to all usages of that class throughout the object graph, which is the expected behavior described in the requirement.

